          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Final stages of the ceasefire deal</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-15-2.png" alt="Final stages of the ceasefire deal" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Mediators are more confident that they are in the final phases of a ceasefire-hostage agreement. The US, Egypt, and Qatar have been trying to mediate an agreement for the last year with little success. The <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-15-01-2025-h2-4-proposed-agreement" target="_blank">proposed agreement</a> has three phases. In the first 42-day phase, Hamas will release 33 hostages, while Israel will free Palestinian prisoners in exchange. Fighting will pause, Israeli forces will withdraw from populated areas, and displaced Palestinians will begin returning home as aid flows into Gaza. The second and third phases frees the rest of the hostages, calls for complete Israeli withdrawal, and eventually starts the reconstruction in Gaza under international oversight and opening of border crossings.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">While all sides are <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-15-01-2025-h2-5-cautiously-optimistic" target="_blank">cautiously optimistic</a> about the deal, the fear looms that the conditions will be broken or the goalposts will be moved at the last minute. Israel’s ex-foreign minister said, “There will never be a perfect deal, and there never was the possibility of one – every deal will come with painful costs.” The death toll has reached over 46,000 in Gaza, and Israeli intelligence estimates that one-third of the remaining hostages are deceased, while some speculate it could be more.</p>
        </mj-text>
