          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Baltic leaders convene</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">On Tuesday, NATO leaders gathered in Helsinki, Finland, to discuss the security in the Baltic Sea. The meeting was called due to recent disruptions believed to be linked to Russia. They announced that they had launched a new mission, <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-15-01-2025-h3-6-baltic-sentry" target="_blank">Baltic Sentry</a>, to enhance the security of undersea cables, pipelines, and telecommunications links in the Baltic Sea. The Baltic Sentry will include frigates, maritime patrol aircraft, and a small fleet of naval drones.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">
          Latvian President Edgars Rinkevics recognized the challenges of providing complete protection, noting that around 2,000 ships transit the waterway daily. However, NATO Secretary General Mark Rutte underlined the <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-15-01-2025-h3-7-importance-of-deterrence" target="_blank">importance of deterrence</a>. German Chancellor Olaf Scholz highlighted the significance of cooperation in tackling these challenges collectively. All the leaders agreed and committed to upholding regional security, countering hybrid warfare, and protecting the vital undersea networks of the Baltic Sea.
</p>
        </mj-text>
    </mj-section>

