          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">
          <strong>🇷🇸 Serbia’s double whammy</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Serbia is facing an energy crisis in two parts. The first part is due to US sanctions on its state-owned oil and gas company, Naftna Industrija Srbije (NIS), which is majority-owned by Russia’s Gazprom. The sanctions demand the complete exit of Russian interests, threatening Serbia’s energy security. Serbia relies heavily on Russian gas but signed a deal to import 400 million cubic meters annually from Azerbaijan in 2024. However, gas supplies from Azerbaijan to Serbia were halted due to a technical issue at BP’s Shah Deniz Alpha platform, affecting Serbia’s daily <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-15-01-2025-br2-9-1-million-cubic-meter" target="_blank">1.7 million cubic meter</a> supply. The restart date remains unclear. Bulgaria's transit gas to Serbia temporarily replaced the shortfall with volumes from Turkey’s Botas.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
