          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">What was the Treaty of Sevres?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-15-3.png" alt="What was the Treaty of Sevres?" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-15-01-2025-f1-10-treaty-of-sevres" target="_blank">Treaty of Sevres</a> was signed on August 10, 1920. It marked the dissolution of the Ottoman Empire and imposed severe territorial, military, and economic restrictions on Turkey. The Ottoman Empire lost extensive territories, including Armenia, Syria, Iraq, Palestine, and Anatolia, which were either handed over to the Allied Powers or became mandates under the League of Nations. The agreement was supposed to form new countries, including the Republic of Armenia, the Kurdish state, and the Kingdom of Hejaz, though only Armenia was formed.
</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The Ottoman Empire did not agree to the terms, which led to the establishment of the <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-15-01-2025-f2-11-turkish-national-movement" target="_blank">Turkish National Movement</a>, led by Kemal Mustafa Ataturk. This movement aimed to overturn the Treaty of Sevres terms and conditions. This goal was achieved by October 1923, and the Republic of Turkey was proclaimed, with Kemal Ataturk as its first president. <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-15-01-2025-f3-12-treat-of-lausanne" target="_blank">The Treaty of Lausanne</a> subsequently replaced the Treaty of Sevres. While the Treaty of Sevres was not long-lasting, it set the course for events in the Middle East and served as a stepping stone for modern-day Turkey.
</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
